<br>
A war for oil in Iraq would not be to protect our current needs. As you and other people have stated, we only get 6% of our oil from Iraq and are really not dependent on them. Iraq's current production levels are not at issue. Oil is ultimately a finite commodity and Iraq is believed to have the largest reserves underneath it once Saudi Arabia is removed from the equation. Some day oil is going to start getting scarce and countries are going to start fighting (arent they already?) over what is left. <br>
<br>
On top of this, there are 6-7 major oil corporations out there and split along nationalist lines. 2 are American, 2 are British, 1 is French, and Russian and China both have their own nationalist interests (I think that is correct..please set it all straight if anyone is an oil expert). These are huge companies with massive clout and resources and want to come out on top when the Iraqi reserves and drilling contracts are divied out. There is also historical issues associated with which oil companies had investments in Iraq that I'm too lazy to lay out that are of interest as well.<br>
<br>
I'm sure some of you will sit here though and say that corporate interests dont affect foreign policy.  <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/utrindle.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Trindle</A> at: 9/20/02 3:49:13 pm<br></i></td></tr></table><br><font color=#333333>- </font><a href=http://pub6.ezboard.com/bnamelesstavern>The Nameless Tavern</a><font color=#333333> - </font><a href=http://pub6.ezboard.com/fnamelesstavernfrm20>Current Affairs</a> <font color=#333333> - </font><br><br><table border=0 align=center><tr><td align=center></td><td><img src="http://www.ezboard.com/image/spacer.gif" width=15 height=1 border=0></td><td align=center></td></tr></table><CENTER><!-- START BOTTOM GAMES AD SCRIPT -->
